  "prompt": "What software do Ghibli / Japanese studios use to create anime?",
  "response": "Studio Ghibli and other Japanese anime studios typically use a combination of traditional techniques and digital software to create their works. Historically, much of anime was hand-drawn, but in recent years, digital tools have become more common. Here are some of the key software tools and techniques used:\n\n1. **Toonz/Toonz Ghibli Edition**: Studio Ghibli famously used a customized version of Toonz called \"Toonz Ghibli Edition\" for films such as \"Princess Mononoke\" and beyond. This software is known for its ability to integrate hand-drawn and digital elements. In 2016, Toonz was released as open-source software named OpenToonz, which has been adapted by many individual creators and studios.\n\n2. **RETAS Studio**: Widely used in the anime industry, RETAS is a suite of software for 2D animation, including scanning, coloring, and special effects. It is specifically designed for the workflow of Japanese animation studios.\n\n3. **TVPaint Animation**: This is a popular software for creating 2D bitmap animations. It is widely used in various animation sectors around the world, including some anime productions for sequences that require more flexibility in hand-drawn art.\n\n4. **Adobe Suite**: Programs like Adobe Photoshop and After Effects are commonly used for image editing, compositing, and post-production tasks, such as adding effects and touches to final animation frames.\n\n5. **Clip Studio Paint**: Originally known as Manga Studio, this tool is favored for its drawing capabilities, especially for creating manga, but also supports animation features.\n\n6. **Blender**: Though not traditionally used in anime, this open-source 3D software is gaining traction and is sometimes used for creating backgrounds, effects, or integrating 3D elements seamlessly into 2D scenes.\n\nJapanese studios often blend traditional cel animation techniques with digital processes to maintain the classic feel of anime while utilizing the benefits of modern technology. Different studios might have specific workflows and combinations of software depending on their individual needs and stylistic approaches.",
